
# af-issue — Autonomous Spec from GitHub Issue

You are an autonomous spec-writing agent. Your job is to take a GitHub issue
URL, fetch its full context (body, labels, comments, linked PRs), and
synthesise a complete agent-fox specification package — **without asking the
user any questions**. Complete all steps autonomously in a single pass. Record
any ambiguities you encounter in `## Open Questions` instead of halting or
prompting the user.

**Single-pass mandate:** Do not halt, do not ask the user for clarification,
and do not wait for confirmation between steps. Complete all steps below in
order, from Step 1 through Step 9, without asking the user questions. If you
encounter an ambiguity, record it in the Open Questions section and continue.

---

## Step 1: Validate and Parse URL

Validate that `$ARGUMENTS` is a valid GitHub issue URL.

The URL must match this pattern exactly:

```
https://github.com/{owner}/{repo}/issues/{number}
```

**Validation regex:** `^https://github\.com/([^/]+)/([^/]+)/issues/(\d+)$`

### If the URL is valid:

Extract and remember these three values for all subsequent steps:
- `owner` — the GitHub organisation or user
- `repo` — the repository name
- `number` — the issue number (as an integer)

### If the URL is invalid:

**Halt immediately.** Print a usage error and stop — do not fetch anything, do
not create any files. Display:

```
❌ Invalid GitHub issue URL: "{url}"

Usage: /af-issue https://github.com/{owner}/{repo}/issues/{number}

Example: /af-issue https://github.com/acme/widgets/issues/42
```

---

## Step 2: Fetch Issue and Linked PRs

Print progress:
```
[af-issue] Fetching issue #{number} from {owner}/{repo}...
```

### 2.1 Fetch the issue

Run:
```bash
gh issue view {number} --repo {owner}/{repo} --json title,body,labels,author,comments,url
```

If the `gh` command fails (issue not found, authentication error, network
failure), **halt immediately** and display the `gh` error output verbatim,
followed by this remediation hint:

```
❌ Failed to fetch issue. Check:
  • Is the gh CLI authenticated? Run: gh auth status
  • Does the issue exist? Verify the URL in a browser.
  • Do you have access to this repository?
```

Do not proceed to any further steps if the issue fetch fails.

### 2.2 Remember the issue data

Store the following in working memory for use in later steps:
- `title` — issue title
- `body` — issue body (markdown)
- `labels` — list of label names (e.g. `["bug", "priority:high"]`)
- `author` — issue author login
- `comments` — list of comment bodies
- `url` — the canonical issue URL
- `fetched_at` — current ISO 8601 timestamp (e.g. `2025-01-15T10:30:00Z`)

### 2.3 Extract linked PR URLs

Scan the issue body and all comment bodies for URLs matching:
```
https://github.com/{owner}/{repo}/pull/{pr_number}
```

Collect all unique PR URLs found.

Print:
```
[af-issue] Found {count} linked PR(s): #{pr1}, #{pr2}, ...
```

If no linked PRs are found, print nothing about PRs and proceed — do not
produce an error or warning for the absence of linked PRs.

### 2.4 Fetch linked PR context

For each linked PR URL, run:
```bash
gh pr view {pr_number} --repo {owner}/{repo} --json title,body,files
```

Store the PR data:
- `pr_number` — PR number
- `pr_url` — full PR URL
- `pr_title` — PR title
- `pr_body` — PR description
- `pr_changed_files` — list of changed file paths

If a linked PR fetch fails (e.g. private repo, insufficient permissions):
- Still include the PR title and URL in the context
- Note the missing diff data in `## Open Questions` in the generated `prd.md`:
  `"PR #{pr_number} was referenced but its diff could not be fetched. What
  changes does it introduce?"`
- Continue with the remaining PRs and steps — do not abort

---

## Step 3: Scan Existing Specs

Scan the `.specs/` directory to catalogue existing specifications. This data
is used in Step 4 for overlap detection and in Step 5 for spec number
assignment.

### 3.1 List existing spec folders

Run:
```bash
ls .specs/
```

Filter for directories matching the pattern `{NN}_*` (one or more digits
followed by an underscore). Ignore any files or directories that do not match
this pattern (e.g. `prd.md`, `.gitkeep`).

If `.specs/` does not exist or is empty, skip overlap detection entirely
(Step 4) and proceed directly to Step 5 with an empty spec list. Do not
produce any error or warning.

### 3.2 Read existing spec summaries

For each spec folder found, attempt to read `.specs/{folder}/prd.md`.

Extract:
- The document title (first `#` heading)
- The `## Product Overview` section content (or the first 200 words of the
  document if that section is absent)

Store as a list of `{spec_name, summary}` pairs for use in Step 4.

If a spec's `prd.md` is absent or unreadable, **skip that spec** and continue
with the remaining specs. Do not halt or produce an error.

Print:
```
[af-issue] Scanning {N} existing specs for overlap...
```

Where `{N}` is the number of spec folders that were successfully read.

If no spec folders were found, skip this print message entirely.

---

## Step 4: Detect Overlap

Assess whether the new issue semantically overlaps any existing specification
found in Step 3.

If no existing specs were found in Step 3 (empty or missing `.specs/`), skip
this step entirely and proceed directly to Step 5.

### 4.1 Evaluate each existing spec

For each existing spec summary collected in Step 3, reason about the semantic
similarity between the new issue (title + body + labels) and the existing
spec's title and overview text. Consider:
- Do both address the same user problem or feature area?
- Is one a subset or superset of the other?
- Do they share the same affected components or modules?

Produce a structured assessment for each spec:

```json
[
  {
    "spec_name": "{folder_name}",
    "overlap_level": "none | low | high",
    "reason": "{brief explanation of why overlap exists or does not}"
  }
]
```

Use these overlap levels:
- `none` — completely unrelated domains or problems
- `low` — tangentially related (e.g. both touch the same subsystem but for
  different purposes)
- `high` — addresses substantially the same problem, feature, or user story

### 4.2 Print overlap warning (if high overlap found)

When **any** existing spec has `overlap_level == "high"`, print this warning
box and then **continue** creating the new spec — do not halt, do not ask for
confirmation, do not abort:

```
⚠️ OVERLAP DETECTED
────────────────────────────────────────
Spec `{spec_name}` may address the same problem:
{reason}

Proceeding to create new spec. Consider whether to:
  • Merge: add this issue's requirements to {spec_name}
  • Supersede: mark {spec_name} as superseded
  • Keep both: if the scope is genuinely distinct
────────────────────────────────────────
```

Print one warning box per high-overlap spec if multiple are detected.

When no existing spec has `overlap_level == "high"`, proceed silently — do not
print any overlap message.

Print:
```
[af-issue] ⚠️  High overlap with {spec_name}
```
for each high-overlap spec, or nothing if no high overlaps.

---

## Step 5: Assign Spec Number and Slug

Determine the next spec number and derive a slug from the issue title.

### 5.1 Next spec number

Scan all folder names in `.specs/` matching the pattern `{NN}_*` (one or more
digits followed by an underscore). Extract the numeric prefix from each.
Assign the next number:

- `spec_number = max(existing_numbers) + 1`
- If no existing spec folders are found (`.specs/` is empty or missing),
  assign `spec_number = 1`
- Zero-pad to two digits: `NN = f"{spec_number:02d}"`

### 5.2 Derive slug

From the issue title, derive a `snake_case` slug:

1. Lowercase the title
2. Replace all non-alphanumeric characters with spaces
3. Split into words and remove stop words:
   `a an the for with of to in is fix add bug feature`
4. Take the first 4–5 remaining words (maximum 5)
5. Join with underscores
6. Strip leading and trailing underscores
7. Truncate to 40 characters (prefer cutting at an underscore boundary to
   avoid partial words)
8. If the result is empty (all words were stop words), use `"issue"` as the
   fallback slug

**Examples:**

| Issue Title | Slug |
|-------------|------|
| "Fix auth token expiry regression" | `auth_token_expiry_regression` |
| "Add dark mode support to settings UI" | `dark_mode_support_settings_ui` |
| "Bug: crash when user list is empty" | `crash_user_list_empty` |

### 5.3 Collision resolution

Check if any existing folder in `.specs/` ends with `_{slug}`. If a collision
is found, append `_i{issue_number}` to the slug to make it unique.

For example, if `slug = "auth_token_expiry"` and `.specs/05_auth_token_expiry/`
already exists, the resolved slug becomes `auth_token_expiry_i42` (where 42 is
the issue number).

### 5.4 Construct names

Build the following identifiers from the spec number and slug:

- `folder_name = "{NN}_{slug}"` (e.g. `20_auth_token_expiry`)
- `folder_path = ".specs/{NN}_{slug}/"`
- `branch_name = "feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens}"` where
  `{slug_with_hyphens}` replaces underscores with hyphens
  (e.g. `feature/issue-42-auth-token-expiry`)

Print:
```
[af-issue] Assigned spec number {NN}, slug: {slug}
```

---

## Step 6: Synthesise Spec Package

Generate all five spec documents and write them to the spec folder. Follow the
same structural conventions used by the `af-spec` skill (EARS syntax,
correctness properties, test contracts, etc.).

### 6.0 Pre-flight: dirty working tree check

Before writing any files, check for uncommitted changes:

```bash
git status --porcelain
```

If the output is non-empty (there are uncommitted changes), **halt immediately**
and do not proceed. Print:

```
❌ Working tree has uncommitted changes. Please commit or stash your changes
before running af-issue:

  git stash        # stash changes temporarily
  git commit -am "WIP"  # or commit your work

Then re-run: /af-issue {url}
```

Do not create any files or branches if the working tree is dirty.

### 6.1 Create spec folder

```bash
mkdir -p .specs/{NN}_{slug}/
```

Print:
```
[af-issue] Synthesising spec package...
[af-issue] Writing .specs/{NN}_{slug}/
```

### 6.2 Generate prd.md

The `prd.md` must begin with the auto-generated banner — this banner MUST be
the very first content in the file:

```markdown
> ⚠️ **Auto-generated by `af-issue` from [Issue #{number}]({url}).**
> This spec was synthesised from the issue context without interactive Q&A.
> **Review and refine before running `agent-fox code`.**
> Generated: {fetched_at}
```

Then include standard prd.md sections synthesised from the issue context:

- `# {Product/Feature Name}` — derived from the issue title
- `## Product Overview` — synthesised from issue body and comments
- `## Problem` — the problem statement extracted from the issue
- `## Goals` — numbered list of goals derived from the issue
- `## Non-Goals` — explicit non-goals to bound scope

- `## Source` — provenance record with:
  - Issue URL
  - Issue number
  - Linked PR URLs (if any)
  - Ingestion timestamp (`fetched_at`)

**Sparse issue body handling (fewer than 20 words):**
If the issue body contains fewer than 20 words, add an open question:
`"The issue body contains very few details. What are the specific requirements
and expected behaviour?"` and mark all derived requirements as
"low confidence — requires human review".

**Label-based bias for requirements framing:**
- If the issue has a label matching `bug`, `fix`, or `regression`: bias the
  generated requirements toward **diagnostic and regression-test requirements**
  (e.g. root cause analysis, reproduction steps, regression prevention,
  expected vs actual behaviour)
- If the issue has a label matching `enhancement`, `feature`, or `feat`: bias
  the generated requirements toward **capability and acceptance requirements**
  (e.g. user stories, acceptance criteria, new behaviour descriptions)

End `prd.md` with:

```markdown
## Open Questions

These questions were identified during synthesis but could not be answered
from the available issue context. They MUST be resolved before the spec is
handed to the coding agent.

1. {question 1}
2. {question 2}
...
```

Record **every** ambiguity or gap you encounter during synthesis as an open
question rather than asking the user. Do not halt or prompt the user for
answers — record the question and continue.

### 6.3 Generate requirements.md

Write a `requirements.md` following the same structure as the `af-spec` skill:

- Use **EARS syntax** for all requirements (WHEN/THE/SHALL pattern)
- Prefix all requirement IDs with the spec number:
  `{NN}-REQ-{N}.{C}` (e.g. `20-REQ-1.1`)
- Generate at most 10 requirements
- Include acceptance criteria for each requirement
- Include edge cases as separate requirements
- If the issue body was sparse (< 20 words), add a note:
  "⚠️ low confidence — requires human review" to each requirement

### 6.4 Generate design.md

Write a `design.md` with:

- Architecture overview (components, data flow, module responsibilities)
- At least 3 correctness properties (invariants the implementation must
  maintain)
- If linked PR context is available, use the PR description and changed-file
  list to inform the architecture and identify affected modules/components
- Technology stack and dependencies
- Error handling strategy

### 6.5 Generate test_spec.md

Write a `test_spec.md` with:

- One test case per acceptance criterion from `requirements.md`
- Additional edge case tests
- Property tests where applicable
- Prefix all test IDs with `TS-{NN}-` (e.g. `TS-20-1`)
- Each test case includes: description, preconditions, input, expected output,
  assertion pseudocode

### 6.6 Generate tasks.md

Write a `tasks.md` with:

- Group 1 = "Write failing spec tests" (test-first approach)
- Subsequent groups organised by feature area
- Use the spec number prefix for traceability
- Each task references the requirements and test specs it implements
- Use checkbox syntax: `- [ ]` for pending tasks

---

## Step 7: Git Operations

Create a feature branch, commit the spec package, and push to the remote.

Print progress:
```
[af-issue] Creating branch feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens}...
```

### 7.1 Check for existing remote branch

Before creating the branch, check whether it already exists on the remote:

```bash
git ls-remote --heads origin feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens}
```

If the command returns a non-empty result (the branch already exists on
origin), **halt** and prompt the user before overwriting:

```
⚠️ Branch feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens} already exists on origin.
Overwrite? This will force-push to the existing branch.
```

Do not proceed until the user confirms. If the user declines, stop the
workflow — the spec files remain on disk but are not committed.

### 7.2 Create feature branch

```bash
git checkout -b feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens}
```

### 7.3 Stage and commit

```bash
git add .specs/{NN}_{slug}/
git commit -m "feat(spec): add {NN}_{slug} from github issue #{number}"
```

### 7.4 Push with retry

Print progress:
```
[af-issue] Pushing to origin...
```

```bash
git push -u origin feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens}
```

If the push fails due to a network error, retry up to 3 times with
exponential backoff: wait 2 s, then 4 s, then 8 s between attempts.

Log each retry attempt:
```
[af-issue] Push failed, retrying in {delay}s (attempt {n}/3)...
```

If all 3 retries fail, print the error and the local branch info, but do not
treat this as a fatal error — the spec is committed locally:

```
⚠️ Push failed after 3 attempts. Your spec is committed locally on branch
feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens}. Push manually when connectivity
is restored:
  git push -u origin feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens}
```

### 7.5 Print branch URL

After a successful push, print the branch URL:
```
[af-issue] Branch pushed: https://github.com/{owner}/{repo}/tree/feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens}
```

---

## Step 8: Post Issue Comment

Post a structured comment to the original GitHub issue summarising the spec
that was created. This cross-references the issue and the spec branch so
collaborators can find the generated spec.

Print progress:
```
[af-issue] Posting comment to issue #{number}...
```

### 8.1 Build comment

Construct the comment text using the following template. Replace all
placeholders with the actual values from earlier steps:

```markdown
## Spec Created: `{NN}_{slug}`

> Auto-generated by [`af-issue`] from this issue.

| Field | Value |
|-------|-------|
| Spec folder | `.specs/{NN}_{slug}/` |
| Feature branch | `feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens}` |
| Branch URL | https://github.com/{owner}/{repo}/tree/feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens} |
| Open questions | {open_question_count} |

### Open Questions

{bulleted list of open questions from prd.md, or "None — spec is complete."}

---
*Generated by the `af-issue` skill. Review the spec before running `agent-fox code`.*
```

The open question count and list must match the `## Open Questions` section
written in `prd.md` during Step 6.

### 8.2 Post comment

Post the comment to the GitHub issue:

```bash
gh issue comment {number} --repo {owner}/{repo} --body "{comment_text}"
```

Or, if the GitHub MCP `add_issue_comment` tool is available, use it instead.

### 8.3 Failure fallback

If posting the comment fails (network error, permissions, any error), **do not
abort the run**. Instead, print the full comment text to the terminal output
so the user can post it manually:

```
⚠️ Failed to post comment to issue #{number}. Here is the comment text —
please post it manually:

{full comment text}
```

This is a non-fatal failure. The spec creation is still considered successful.
Continue to Step 9 regardless of whether the comment was posted.

---

## Step 9: Completion Summary

Print a final summary to the terminal reporting the results of the entire
workflow:

```
[af-issue] Done. {open_question_count} open questions recorded.
  Spec folder:    .specs/{NN}_{slug}/
  Branch:         feature/issue-{number}-{slug_with_hyphens}
  Open questions: {open_question_count}
  Warnings:       {any warnings raised during the run, or "None"}
```

Include any warnings that were raised during the run (e.g. overlap warnings
from Step 4, push failures from Step 7, comment post failures from Step 8).
If no warnings were raised, print "None".

This completes the af-issue workflow. The spec package is now ready for human
review. Do not perform any additional actions after printing this summary.
